The territories of some major [[List of Celtic tribes|Celtic tribes]] of the late La Tène period are labeled.]]
The appearance of '''Celts in Transylvania''' can be traced to the later [[La Tène period]] (c. 4th century BC).{{sfn|Koch|2005|p=549}}
Excavation of the great La Tène [[necropolis]] at [[Apahida]], [[Cluj County]], by [[S. Kovacs]] at the turn of the 20th century revealed the first evidence of [[Ancient Celtic culture|Celtic culture]] in Romania. The 3rd&ndash;2nd century BC site is remarkable for its cremation burials and chiefly wheel-made funeral vessels.{{sfn|Zirra|1976|p=4}}

A historical timeline of the [[Celts]] of Transylvania can be derived from archaeological finds at La Tène, but there are almost no ancient records that allow reconstruction of political events in the area. The Celts exercised politico-military rule over Transylvania between the 4th and 2nd century BC and brought with them a more advanced iron-working technology. They were also responsible for the spread of the [[potter's wheel]] into a much wider area than the one they occupied.{{sfn|Nagler|Pop|Barbulescu|2005|p=78}}

== History ==

[[File:Celt tool Transyslvania.jpg|thumb|left|250px|Celtic socketed axes and tools from the Bronze Age in Transylvania, Romania]]
Large areas of ancient Dacia, which were populated early in the First [[Iron Age]] by [[Thracian]] people, were affected by a massive migration of Iranian [[Scythians]] moving east to west during the first half of the first millennium BC. They were followed by a second equally large wave of [[Celts]] migrating west to east.{{sfn|Zirra|1976|p=1}} Celts arrived in northwestern Transylvania in around 400&ndash;350 BC as part of their great migration eastwards.{{sfn|Nagler|Pop|2005|p=79}} When Celtic warriors first penetrated these territories, the group seem to have [[merged]] with the domestic population of early [[Dacians]] and assimilated many [[Hallstatt]] cultural traditions.{{sfn|Zirra|1976|p=13}}

=== 4th century BC ===
The second half of the 4th century BC saw the Middle La Tène Celtic culture emerge in north-western and central Dacia, a development reflected especially in burials of the period.{{sfn|Koch|2005|p=549}} Celtic artifacts dating to this time have been discovered at [[Turdaş]], [[Haţeg]] and [[Mediaş]] in modern-day Romania.
By 1976, the number of Celtic sites found in Transylvania had reached about 150, indicating a significant [[La Tène]] population surpassed only by the Dacians.{{sfn|Zirra|1976|p=5}} These sites are mostly cemeteries.{{sfn|Koch|2005|p=549}} Archaeological investigations have highlighted several warrior graves with military equipment, suggesting that an elite Celtic military force penetrated the region.{{sfn|Koch|2005|p=549}}

Celtic vestiges are found concentrated in the Transylvanian plateau and plain, as well as the upper [[Someş]] basin, whereas the surrounding valleys of [[Haţeg]], [[Hunedoara]], [[Făgăraş]], [[Bârsa]], [[Sf. Gheorghe]] and [[Miercurea Ciuc|Ciuc]] have neither [[List of necropoleis|necropoleis]] nor settlements but only tombs or isolated items.{{sfn|Sîrbu|Arsenescu|2006|p=165}} This indicates that Celts occupied the territory between [[Mureş County|Mureş]] and [[Someş]], west of the [[Apuseni Mountains]], and the plains and plateau in the intra-Carpathian space along with the valley in the upper basin of [[Someş]].{{sfn|Sîrbu|Arsenescu|2006|p=165}} Nevertheless, these valleys, as well as those of [[Banat]] and [[Maramureş]], have also yielded contemporary Dacian findings.{{sfn|Sîrbu|Arsenescu|2006|p=165}}

Of the Celtic cemeteries excavated, the most important are those in [[Ciumeşti]] and [[Pişcolt]] ([[Satu Mare County]]) and [[Matei, Bistriţa-Năsăud|Fântânele]] ([[Bistriţa-Năsăud County]]).{{sfn|Koch|2005|p=448}} These contain over 150 graves compared to the average of 50&ndash;70.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.enciclopedia-dacica.ro/invaziile/celtii/celtii.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-12-29 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110126195901/http://www.enciclopedia-dacica.ro/invaziile/celtii/celtii.htm |archivedate=2011-01-26 |df= }}</ref> Necropoleis have also been found at [[Sanislău]] ([[Satu Mare County]]), [[Curtuişeni]] ([[Bihor County]]), [[Galaţii Bistriţei]] ([[Bistriţa-Năsăud County]]), and [[Braşov]] ([[Braşov County]]).{{sfn|Glodariu|1997|p=78}}

* Twenty-three of the oldest graves from the extensive [[Fântânele, Mureş]] cemetery in [[Mureş County]] have been dated to the beginning of the 4th century BC. Among European Celtic cemeteries, this one is second only to [[Munsingen]] in size. The [[Dacians|Geto-Dacian]] population is also represented through a full range of contemporary native pottery types.{{sfn|Nandris|1976|p=730}}
* Finds from [[Pişcolt]] reveal that the inhabitants of settlements in the area practiced inhumation, or reuse of a pre-existing barrow or grave, as a type of burial.
* At [[Ciumeşti]] cemetery, of the 34 graves excavated, 21 were simple [[cremation]]s in pits, seven featured inhumations, while the remains of six cremations had been buried in urns. The number and type of finds in the graves differed in each case.{{sfn|Koch|2005|p=448}} Principal among the grave-goods was an iron warrior's helmet of eastern Celtic type as well as a socketed spear, a pair of Hellenistic [[greave]]s and a suit of chain mail, to which a small bronze disc had been attached as its central feature with S-shaped motifs arranged in a series of symmetrical panels around its edge.{{sfn|Harding|2007|p=128}}

In Transylvania, the Celts shifted from inhumation to cremation, either through natural progression or because of Dacian influence.{{sfn|Nagler|Pop|2005|p=79}} Almost without exception, the necropoleis so far studied are bi-ritual, although cremation appears to be more prevalent than inhumation.{{sfn|Zirra|1976|p=20}} The Celts in Dacia certainly cremated their dead from the second La Tène period onwards{{sfn|Pârvan|1928|p=148}} but Celtic inhumations appear no older than [[pit-grave]] cremations in any of the cemeteries.{{sfn|Zirra|1976|p=21}} It is impossible to say whether the Celts turned away from the practice of cremation as the [[Scythians]] had.{{sfn|Pârvan|1928|p=148}} Although less frequent, inhumation still occurred as a constant practice even during the final stage of Celtic inhabitation of this territory.{{sfn|Zirra|1976|p=21}}

Celtic settlements had a rural character with such sites found in [[Mediaș]], [[Moreşti]], ([[Mureş County]]) and [[Ciumeşti]].

[[File:3-bc map elznik.jpg|right|thumbnail|300px| Movements of the Celts in Transylvania in 3rd century]]
[[File:Bronze age weapons Romania.jpg|thumb|left|250px|Bronze Age and Iron Age artefacts from Romania.]]

Expansion of Celtic groups in the area may be related to [[Gallic invasion of the Balkans|their invasion of the Balkans]] around 335 BC, when a massive colonization of the [[Tisza|Tisa]] plain and the [[Transylvanian Plateau]] occurred following the death of [[Lysimachus]]. However, the eastward movement of the Celts into Transylvania used a different route from the one taken by the hordes that attacked the Balkans. {{sfn|Cunliffe|1986|p=131}}

Celts did not occupy all intra-Carpathian areas of Transylvania, stopping short of the [[Maramureş]] Depression for instance, where excavations have uncovered Dacian fortifications from the 4th and 3rd centuries BC.{{sfn | Pop | 2006| p=43}}
As regards Celtic influence on local Daco-Getic culture, [[Vasile Pârvan]] has stated that the latter is wholly indebted to Celtic traditions and that the "La Tene-ization" of these northern Tracians was a cultural phenomenon primarily due to the Celtic population who settled the area. {{sfn| Zirra |1976 |p=4}}

=== 3rd - 2nd century BC ===
Archaeological sites of the 3rd and 2nd centuries BC reveal a pattern of co-existence and fusion between the bearers of La Tène culture and the indigenous Dacians. Domestic dwellings exhibit a mixture of Celtic and Dacian pottery while several Celtic graves contain Dacian type vessels.{{sfn|Koch|2005|p=549}} At Celtic sites in Dacia, finds show that the native population imitated [[Celtic art]] forms that they admired, but remained firmly and fundamentally Dacian in their culture.{{sfn|MacKendrick|2000|p=50}}

Dacian archaeological finds in the Transylvania area increase in number from the middle of the 2nd century BC.{{sfn|Sîrbu|Arsenescu|2006|p=165}}

=== 2nd&ndash;1st century BC ===
[[File:Boians.png|upright=1.5|right|thumbnail|300px|Migratory movements of the Celtic Boii]]

During the first half of the 2nd century BC, [[Pompeius Trogus]] writes in his ''Historiae Philippicae'' of a Dacian king, [[Oroles]], who fought against Celtic incursions.{{sfn|Berresford Ellis|1996|p=61}} Oroles is recorded as resisting the intrusion of the [[Bastarnae]], a people now generally considered to be of Germanic origin but who were in fact Celto-Germanic and, according to [[Livy]], spoke a [[Celtic language]].{{sfn|Berresford Ellis|1996|p=257}} The Bastarnae moved from [[Silesia]] into what is now central and northern [[Moldavia]].{{sfn|Berresford Ellis|1996|p=257}}

Pompeius Trogus along with [[Justin (historian)|Justin]] also record the rise in Dacian authority prior to 168 BC under the leadership of King [[Rubobostes]].<ref>Barry Cunliffe (1987)142</ref>{{sfn|Berresford Ellis|1996|p=61}}<ref>John T. Koch (2005) 549</ref>

Around 150 BC, La Tène material disappears from the area. This is concurrent with ancient writings, which mention the rise of Dacian authority. This ended Celtic domination and it is possible that the Celts were forced out of Dacia. On the other hand, some scholars have posited that the Transylvanian Celts remained but merged with the local culture and thereafter ceased to be distinctive.{{sfn|Koch|2005|p=549}}{{sfn|MacKendrick|2000|p=50}}

The boundary between the Celts and Dacians near the [[Tisza|River Tisa]] is depicted in 2nd century BC pottery found at [[Pecica]] in [[Arad County]], a prosperous trading center at the confluence of the two peoples.{{sfn|Turnock|1988|p=42}}

=== 1st century BC ===
[[File:Dacia around 60-44 BC during Burebista, including campaigns - French.png|thumb|250px|left|Map of Dacia during Burebista's time (60-44 BC) including the campaigns against Celtic Boii and Teurisci]]
A classic period of Geto-Dacian La Tène culture began in the 1st century BC centered around the city of [[Sarmizegetusa Regia]] in south-western Transylvania.{{sfn|Berresford Ellis|1996|p=258}} Dacian king [[Burebista]] defeated the Celtic [[Boii]] and [[Taurisci]] tribes between 60&ndash;59 BC.{{sfn|Nandris|1976|p=731}} However, some archaeological finds in Dacian settlements and fortifications feature imported Celtic vessels and others made by Dacian potters imitating Celtic prototypes. These discoveries in sites from regions north and west of Transylvania show that relations between the Dacians and the Celts continued in the period 1st century BC-1st century AD.{{sfn|Koch|2005|p=550}}

During Burebista's time, the Dacians became closer to the remaining Celtic populations than they had been when the Celts ruled Transylvania. Evidence from the earlier period shows Celtic burials and settlements with only occasional Dacian elements, while Dacian settlements with Celtic finds are infrequent. This situation reversed after Burebista's conquest when a distinctive hybrid Celtic-Dacian culture emerged on the [[Hungarian plain]] and in the Slovakian regions.{{sfn|Shchukin|1989|p=88}}

Most of the Celts were absorbed into the Geto-Dacian population and contributed to Dacian cultural development. These Celtic tribes, who were skilled in iron exploitation and processing, also introduced the potter's wheel to the area, thereby contributing to acceleration of the development of Dacia.{{sfn|Berresford Ellis|1996|p=61}} By this time, prosperous Celtic communities had spread over the whole territory of modern Romania.{{sfn|Berresford Ellis|1996|p=257}}

[[File:Cesare prima Gallia 58 a.C. jpg.jpg|thumb|300px|right|Dacian (orange) and Celtic tribes (green) in the [[Roman republic]] and its neighbours in 58 BC]]

=== 2nd century AD ===
{{See also| List of Roman auxiliary regiments | Alpinorum auxiliary regiments }}

By the 2nd century, Celtic military and civilian groups from Roman Empire provinces had moved into the area of Transylvania that also had become part of the Empire, as part of Roman Dacia, by 106 AD. {{sfn|Husar |1995|p=134}} They were probably Latin-speaking groups with [[Celts|Celtic]] substratum who also participated in the [[Ancient Rome|Roman]] military campaigns in [[Dacia]].{{sfn|Husar |1995|p=131 }}

[[Roman Dacia]] consisted of eastern and southeastern Transylvania, the [[Banat]] and [[Oltenia]] regions of modern Romania but excluded the rest of Dacia. The presence of Celts here is mainly illustrated by the composition of both the legions and cohorts. [[Legio XIII Gemina]] came from the Celtic zone of [[Vindabona]] and contained some Celtic elements. Troops from Roman Celtic and Germanic provinces were the most numerous of the auxiliary troops.{{sfn|Husar |1995|p=134 }}{{sfn|Husar |1995|p=134}} (See also [[List of Roman auxiliary regiments]])

The several cohorts and alae Gallorum attested in diplomas and inscriptions reveal the large number of Gauls who were recruited by Romans, some of whom were moved to Transylvania (i.e. [[Cohors II Gallorum Dacica equitata]] in Dacia Superior later organized as Dacia Porolissensis).{{sfn| Southern |2007|p=143}}{{sfn|Husar |1995|p=134}} Some units were recruited from single Gallic or Germanic tribes (i.e. Germanic [[Batavi (Germanic tribe)|Batavi]] formed Cohors III Batavorum "3rd Cohort of Batavi").{{sfn| Southern |2007|p=143}}

The following are military units with some Celtic-speaking elements stationed in this region:

* [[Legio XIII Gemina]] located at [[Alba Iulia|Apulum]] the Latin name of the Dacian settlement [[Apulon]], ([[Alba Iulia]]).{{sfn| Garcia | 2010 |p=467 }}
* [[Cohors I Alpinorum equitata]]: When stationed in Dacia Superior, they were garrisoned at [[Castra of Sărățeni|Sărăţeni]], [[Mureș County|Mureş]]. After 144 AD they were moved to [[Castra of Călugăreni|Călugăreni]] {{sfn| Spaul| 2000 |p=260}}
* Military detachments [[Alpine regiments of the Roman army|I Vindelicorum c.R. eq]]: Formed by the Celtic [[Vindelici]], it is attested at [[Cumidava]] on the site of modern [[Rasnov]], by an inscription "Vindelicorum Cumidavensis Alexandriana".{{sfn| Piso |2005|p=133}} Other detachments of [[Alpine regiments of the Roman army|I Vindelicorum c.R. eq]] were located at [[Tibiscum]].{{sfn| Garcia | 2010 |p=467 }}
* Alpinorum and cohors VIII Raetorum are recorded in Dacia superior in diploma from 136/38 having been attested in Dacia in 114 and 110 AD. {{sfn| Holder |2006|p=750}}
* [[Cohors II Gallorum Dacica equitata]], Dacia Superior. A number of stamps of Ala Gallorum were found at Borosneul Mare [[Covasna]].{{sfn| Cataniciu |1981|p=45}}
* Cohors V Lingonum (Celtic [[Lingones]]): They were located at [[Moigrad-Porolissum]].{{sfn| Spaul | 2000 |p=575}}

[[File:Roman period tribes in Illyria and Lower Pannonia.png|thumb|left|250px|Celts in Illyria, Pannonia, including parts of Dacia (modern Transylvania)]]

== Celtic tribes in Transylvania ==
In the vicinity of 2nd century BC Transylvania, the Celtic [[Boii]] settled in the northern area of [[Dunántúl]], in modern-day southern Slovakia and in the northern region of Hungary around the centre of modern-day Bratislava. {{sfn|Nagler|Pop|Barbulescu|2005 |p=78}} Boii tribal union members the [[Taurisci]] and the [[Anarti]] lived in northern Dacia{{sfn|Nagler|Pop|Barbulescu|2005 |p=78}} with the core of the Anarti tribe found in the area of the Upper Tisa.{{sfn|Oledzki|2000 |p=525 }} The [[Anartophracti]] from modern southeast Poland are considered part of the Anarti.{{sfn|Oledzki|2000 |p=525 }} [[Scordiscan]] Celts dwelling southeast of the [[Iron Gates]] of the Danube may be considered a part of the Transylvanian Celtic culture.{{sfn|Olmsted|2001 |p=11}} A group of [[Britogauls]] also moved into the area.{{sfn|Giurescu|Nestorescu|1981|p=33}}

Celts penetrated first into western Dacia, then as far as north-west and central Transylvania.{{sfn|Oltean|2007|p=47}}{{sfn|Giurescu|Nestorescu|1981|p=33 }} A large number of archaeological finds indicate a sizeable Celtic population settling for a long period among the natives.{{sfn|Nagler|Pop|Barbulescu|2005 |p=78}} The archaeological evidence shows that these Eastern Celts were absorbed into the Geto-Dacian population.{{sfn|Oltean|2007|p=47}}{{sfn|Berresford Ellis|1996|p=61}}

A geographic reference by [[Ptolemy]] from the 2nd century AD indicates that the Anarti were settled on the northwestern edge of Dacia with the Teurisci bordering them on the east, and further east there were the [[Costoboci]].{{sfn|Oledzki|2000 |p=525 }}

== Celtic art in Transylvania ==
[[File:Celtic Helmet from Satu Mare, Romania.jpg|thumb|right|300px|The [[Celts|Celtic]] Helmet from [[Ciumeşti]], near [[Satu Mare County|Satu Mare]], [[Romania]] (northern [[Dacia]]), an [[Iron Age]] raven totem helmet, dated around the 4th century BC. A similar helmet is depicted on the [[Gundestrup cauldron]], being worn by one of the mounted warriors (detail tagged here <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/28433765@N07/3219662507/|title=celtic god Teutates|author=|date=|website=flickr.com|accessdate=20 April 2018}}</ref>). See also an [https://www.flickr.com/photos/celtico/3751742958/ illustration of Brennos wearing a similar helmet].]]

=== Helmet of Ciumeşti ===
One of the best known and most often reproduced pieces of Celtic art is the helmet found in a warrior chieftain's grave at [[Ciumeşti]] (now [[Satu Mare County]], Romania).{{sfn|Koch|2005|p=448}} The Ciumeşti helmet is half-round with a neck protector and was hammered out of a single bronze plate with the cheek pieces bolted on afterwards. A bronze spike protrudes through the top of the helmet to which is fixed a cylinder on which a bird perches. The legs and the underpart of the head are cast while the remainder is hammered. The eyes are yellow ivory with a red enamel pupil, fastened in with bitumen. Overall the bird is {{Convert|13|in}} in length and has a wingspan of {{Convert|9|in}}.{{sfn|MacKendrick|2000|p=52}}

The bird, whether raven, eagle or falcon, is a known Celtic totem. {{sfn|MacKendrick|2000|p=52}} The representation of the bird of prey hovering over the Ciumeşti helmet had a profound supernatural significance since in the world of the La Tène Celts based on the ample documentary evidence endorsing the special ritual associations of birds.{{sfn|Harding|2007|p=20 }} Note that the Gundestrup cauldron, now in [[Copenhagen]], also depicts a bird crest on helmets.{{sfn|MacKendrick|2000|p=52}}

Wilcox and McBride mentioned that their illustration of the iron Gallic warrior's helmet of the middle La Tène period had been reconstructed on the basis of the Ciumesti helmet.{{sfn| Wilcox | McBride |1985|p=46 and 27, illustration B3 (seen also on the book cover)}}

[[File:Gundestrupkarret3.jpg|thumb|300px|left| Gundestrup cauldron inside panel. One of the scenes provides a good parallel to the Ciumesti bird helmet {{sfn|Koch|2006|p=157}}]]

=== Other Transylvanian helmets ===
Four other helmets of bronze or iron have also been found in the intra-Carpathian area at [[Silivaş, Alba|Silivas]] ([[Alba County]]), [[Apahida]] ([[Cluj County]]), [[Ocna Mureş]] ([[Sibiu County]]) and [[Valea Haţegului]] ([[Hunedoara County]]). All these helmets are of the [[Waldalgesheim Style]] developed by the La Tène and date from the period when semi-victorious Celtic armies returned from the [[Balkan Peninsula]] and settled on the [[Pannonian Plain]] and in Transylvania.{{sfn|Zirra|1976|p=26}}

Helmets with reinforced crests are typically eastern Celtic and can be traced as they spread from the western margins of Taurisci territory at [[Mihovo]], to be subsequently used by the [[Scordisci]] at [[Batina]] and throughout Transylvania (Apahida, Ciumeşti).{{sfn|Koch|2006|p=157}}

=== Other Celtic art objects ===
[[File:Orastie Celtic cauldron.JPG|thumb|right | The wheeled [[cauldron]] or ''Kesselwagen'' [[Orăştie]], [[Romania]], used as a crematory urn, during the later Celtic Bronze Age. It is drawn by water-birds{{sfn|Harding|2007|p=20}} ]]
[[File:Helmet and standard.JPG|thumb|left| The Dacian war trumpet, as shown on the Roman Emperor [[Trajan's Column]] at Rome 116 AD, is a Celtic-style [[Carnyx]].{{sfn|Pârvan|1928|p=126}} (n.b. The Celtic carnyx appears on the [[Gundestrup cauldron]]).]]
[[File:Hallein Keltenmuseum - Lure.jpg|200px|thumb|left|Celts' carnyx at [[Lure, Haute-Saône|Lure]]]]

A wheeled [[cauldron]] or ''Kesselwagen'', used as a crematory urn during the later Celtic Bronze Age ritual assemblage, was found at [[Orăştie]], Romania. This one is notionally drawn by teams of water-birds.{{sfn|Harding|2007|p=20}}

A coin type from Ciumesti shows a warrior wearing a wild boar crest on his helmet {{sfn|MacKendrick|2000|p=52}}

The Dacian war trumpet, as shown on the Roman Emperor [[Trajan's Column]] at Rome 116 AD, is a Celtic-style [[carnyx]].{{sfn|Pârvan|1928|p=126}}

=== Plastic Style ===
High-relief ornamental designs known as the "Plastic Style" are found on warriors' equipment from [[Pişcolt]], comprising a shield with an ornate handle and shield-boss as well as a sword in an ornamented scabbard with traces of a "dragon-pair" motif.{{sfn|Harding|2007|p=118-121 }} This motif is one of the genuinely pan-European themes of early La Tène art and is found embellishing the upper end of scabbard front-plates from southeast Britain to Transylvania.{{sfn|Harding|2007|p=102}}

=== Influences of the Thracian / Dacian style in works of Celts ===
[[File:Figures with horns on the Gundestrup Cauldron.jpg|thumb|200px|right|Figures with horns / carnyx on the Gundestrup Cauldron]]

From at least the 3rd century BC, the undoubted interaction between the La Tène Celtic and [[Dacia]]n worlds can be considered a [[Thracian]] / [[Dacia]]n influence on works of Celtic craftsmanship, or even imports from these regions.{{sfn|Harding|2007|p=130}} Such influence may be seen in the great silver ring from [[Trichtingen]], near Stuttgart. Silver is not the prime medium of high-status craftsmanship in the Celtic world but is characteristic of Thracian / Dacian metal-working.{{sfn|Harding|2007|p=130 }}

Moreover, the Ciumeşti Helmet and numerous later artifacts made partly or wholly of silver (''fibulae'' or belt plates), clearly demonstrate the interaction between Thracian and Dacian schools of ornamental metalwork with the Celtic La Tène tradition.{{sfn|Koch|2005|p=157}}

Numerous studies of the artwork of the [[Gundestrup cauldron]], provide comparative analyses of Celtic and Thracian traditions. Images on the cauldron have many features that are common to the Celtic and Thracian corpus of art while exotic animal motifs suggest an oriental influence. Although the design has features of Celtic belief and iconography, it appears to have been made by Thracian smiths in Dacia or Thrace, in the lower Danube region, according to their own traditions. The cauldron may have been commissioned by a member of Celtic community.{{sfn|Bradley|2009|p=24}}{{sfn| Allen|Reynolds |2001|p=3}}

== Society ==

=== Coins ===
Mythological symbols feature on the earliest Celtic coins, which were struck in what is now modern Transylvania, Romania. This would result in the minting of later Celtic coins elsewhere that are considered miniature works of art.{{sfn|Duffy|1999|p=43 and 226}} Evidence of the [[Hallstatt]] culture in Dacia, as well as the political and economic rule of the Celts, suggests that it was the Celts, not the Dacians, who minted these silver coins based on the Macedonian [[Tetradrachm]]ae of [[Philip II of Macedon|Philip II]] (r. 382&ndash;336 BC). According to [[Zirra]], this theory is supported by numismatist, C. Pedra, who argues that the Celts of Dacia first began minting coins in the mid-3rd to the mid-2nd century BC, after which, native [[Mint (coin)|mints]] lasted until the early decades of the 1st century BC.{{sfn|Zirra|1976|p=26}}

=== Religion ===
[[File:epona.jpg|thumb|200px|left|Epona (the horse-goddess) as seen at the [[Historical Museum of Bern]], the most important Celtic cult attested to in Roman Dacia, 2nd century AD]]

The Dacian priestly class may have influenced the [[druids]] of the Celts{{sfn|Waldman|Mason|2006|p=210}} with the important Christian author [[Hippolytus of Rome]] (170&ndash;236 AD), claiming that the druids adopted the teachings of [[Pythagoras]] through the intermediacy of [[Zalmoxis]].{{sfn|Berresford Ellis|1996|p=44}}

Roman Dacia's [[Pantheon (gods)|pantheon]] includes Celtic divinities brought to the province by both military and civilian elements.{{sfn|Husar |1995|p=136 }} The most important Celtic cult attested in the new province is that of the horse-goddess [[Epona]].{{sfn|MacKendrick|2000|p=190}} Specific epithets in her honor as ''Augusta'', ''Regina'' and ''Sancta'' are found on inscriptions from [[Alba Iulia]], on the site of ancient settlement [[Apulon]] (Latin [[Apulum (castra)|Apulum]]).{{sfn|Husar |1995|p=139}}

The stag-horned [[Cernunnos]], one of the "great gods" of the Celts, was also known in the area according to two testimonies, one of them calling him ''Iupiter Cernenus'', a name found nowhere else in the Empire. However, Cernunnos also has funereal attributions, not only as a protector of tombs but also as a [[psychopompos]] god.{{sfn|Husar |1995|p=138 }}

References to [[Apollo Grannus]] and [[Sirona]], divinities widespread in [[Gallia]] and on the Upper Danube as protectors of health are also recorded in Roman Dacia.{{sfn|Husar |1995|p=136}}

=== Language ===
{{Dacia series}}
Two out of the sixty known [[List of Dacian plant names|Dacian plant names]] are considered of Celtic origin, e.g. ''propeditla'' ‘[[cinquefoil]]’ (cf. [[Gaulish language|Gaulish]] ''pempedula'', [[Cornish language|Cornish]] ''pympdelenn'', [[Breton language|Breton]] ''pempdelienn''), and ''dyn'' ‘[[nettle]]’.{{sfn|Hehn|1976 [1885]|p=428}}

Celtic nomenclature carries the same [[Onomastics|onomastic]] weight as that of the Celto-Germanic cults in the religion of Roman Dacia.{{sfn|Husar |1995|p=131}}

