'''Francis Joseph Collin''' (born November 3, 1944 in [[Chicago, Illinois]]) is an American former political activist and Midwest coordinator with the [[National Socialist White People's Party]]. After being ousted for being part Jewish (which he denied), Collin founded in 1970, the [[National Socialist Party of America]].<ref>{{cite book|first=Elizabeth|last=Wheaton|title=Codename GREENKILL: The 1979 Greensboro Killings|publisher=[[University of Georgia Press]]|location=Athens, Georgia|date=1988|ISBN=978-0820309354|pages=3-4}}</ref> In the late 1970s, its plan to march in the predominantly [[Jews in America|Jewish]] suburb of [[Skokie, Illinois]] was challenged, but the [[ACLU]] defended its freedom of speech and assembly in a case that reached the [[United States Supreme Court]]. The court in ''[[National Socialist Party of America v. Village of Skokie]]'' (1979), a major [[First Amendment to the United States Constitution|First Amendment]] decision, ruled that the party had a right to march and to display a [[swastika]], despite local opposition. After Collin was convicted and sentenced in 1979 for [[child molestation]], he lost his position in the party.<ref name="Kaplan2000">{{cite book|last=Kaplan|first=Jeffrey|title=Encyclopedia of White Power: A Sourcebook on the Radical Racist Right|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nNWbbhUYv8oC&pg=PA62|accessdate=21 January 2014|date=2000|publisher=[[Rowman & Littlefield]]|location=Lanham, Maryland|isbn=9780742503403|pages=62–}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Steiger|first1=Brad|last2=Steiger|first2=Sherry|title=Conspiracies and Secret Societies: The Complete Dossier|date=2012|edition=2nd|publisher=Visible Ink Press|location=Detroit, Michigan|isbn=978-1578593682|page=18|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=pPC_yNQew98C&pg=PT98&dq=%22Frank+collin%22+convicted+children%7Csodomy&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CCUQ6AEwAWoVChMIvfOrp_mExgIV5i7bCh2UUgDx#v=onepage&q=%22Frank%20collin%22%20convicted%20children%7Csodomy&f=false|quote=In 1979 Collin’s ambition to lead a new Nazi America was thwarted when he was arrested, convicted, and sent to prison on child molestation charges.}}</ref>

After being released early on parole from prison, Collin created a new career as a writer, publishing numerous books under the pen name '''Frank Joseph.''' He wrote [[New Age]] and "[[hyperdiffusionist]]" works supporting the hypothesis that [[Old World]] peoples had migrated to [[North America]] in ancient times and created its complex [[indigenous peoples|indigenous]] societies. This thesis is rejected by mainstream scholars.

==Early life==
Collin was born and grew up in [[Chicago, Illinois]], where he went to local schools. His father, Max Frank Collin, born Max Simon Cohn in [[Munich]] on August 23, 1913,<ref>{{cite news|first=Ron|last=Grossman|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/opinion/commentary/ct-neo-nazi-skokie-march-flashback-perspec-0312-20170310-story.html#|title=Flashback: 'Swastika war': When the neo-Nazis fought in court to march in Skokie|newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]]|publisher=[[Tronc]]|location=Chicago, Illinois|date=March 10, 2017|accessdate=September 14, 2018}}</ref> the son of Jewish parents who later perished in the [[Shoah]], was a survivor of [[Dachau concentration camp|Dachau]].<ref>{{cite book |first1=Grant |last1=Pick |title=The People Are the News: Grant Pick’s Chicago Stories |date=2008 |publisher=[[Northwestern University Press]]|location=Evanston, Illinois |isbn=9780810124455 |page=68 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=9h1oRbDaXwkC&pg=PA65&dq=%22Frank+Collin%22+Jewish+father+dachau&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi6vJyBpt3bAhXHA8AKHQHuBB4Q6AEILzAB#v=onepage&q=%22Frank%20Collin%22%20Jewish%20father%20dachau&f=false |accessdate=18 June 2018 |language=en}}</ref> His mother, Virginia Gertrude née Hardyman (b. at Chicago on August 18, 1920), was Catholic.<ref name="Peters">{{cite book |first1=John Durham |last1=Peters |title=Courting the Abyss: Free Speech and the Liberal Tradition |date=2010 |publisher=[[University of Chicago Press]] |location=Chicago, Illinois|isbn=9780226662756 |page=159 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=YYVU1Wnw5k8C&pg=PT167&dq=Frank+Collin+Max+Cohn&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi3q8DPod3bAhXIbMAKHbh8DMgQ6AEIRjAG#v=onepage&q=Frank%20Collin%20Max%20Cohn&f=false |accessdate=18 June 2018 |language=en}}</ref>

==National Socialist organizations and the Skokie march==
As a young man, Collin in the 1960s joined [[George Lincoln Rockwell]]'s [[American Nazi Party|National Socialist White People's Party]].<ref name="Kaplan2000"/> He became the Midwest coordinator.<ref name="Durham2007">{{cite book|last=Durham|first=Martin|title=White Rage: The Extreme Right and American Politics|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=I4mJVPVHJLwC&pg=PA23|accessdate=21 January 2014|date=2007-10-23|publisher=[[Routledge]]|location=London, England|isbn=9780203012581|pages=23–}}</ref> He broke with the NSWPP due to a disagreement with Rockwell's successor, [[Matt Koehl]],<ref name="Kaplan2000"/> who was elected as the party leader by popular vote after Rockwell was [[assassinations|assassinated]] on August 25, 1967.  The falling out stemmed in part from published accounts by Max Collin, Frank's father, who said that he was a Jewish [[Holocaust]] survivor and had changed his name from Cohen (or Cohn) to Collin.<ref name="Watia">{{cite news|first=Victor|last=Watia|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1665&dat=19700701&id=XII0AAAAIBAJ&sjid=ZSQEAAAAIBAJ&pg=7108,7360267|title=Frank Collin is Leader of Own Party|newspaper=[[Times-News (Burlington, North Carolina)|The Times-News]]|publisher=[[New Media Investment Group]]|location=Burlington, North Carolina|agency=[[United Press International]]|date=July 1, 1970|accessdate=January 23, 2014}}</ref><ref name="UPI"/> Frank Collin denied having Jewish roots and maintained that his father was not telling the truth.<ref name="UPI">{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1243&dat=19700424&id=pgBYAAAAIBAJ&sjid=E_cDAAAAIBAJ&pg=2335,3773716|title=Nazi denies Jewish blood, but dad claims otherwise|authors=UPI|newspaper=[[The Bulletin]]|publisher=Western Communications|location=Bend, Oregon|date=April 24, 1970|accessdate=January 23, 2014}}</ref>

In 1970, Collin set up another organization, the [[National Socialist Party of America]], later known as the [[American Nazi Party]]. It attracted other disaffected members of the NSWPP,<ref name="Kaplan2000"/> as well as Michael Allen, [[Gary Lauck]] and [[Harold Covington]].<ref name="Kaplan2000"/> Covington helped buy a building for the group which they called Rockwell Hall,<ref name="Kaplan2000"/> where Collin and some other members lived in a barracks in upper floor.<ref name="UPI"/> Collin ran for [[alderman]] of Chicago in 1975 and pulled 16% of the vote.<ref name="Kaplan2000"/>

The NSPA began holding anti-black demonstrations in Chicago's [[Marquette Park (Chicago)|Marquette Park]].<ref name="Marcovitz2010">{{cite book|first=Hal|last=Marcovitz|title=Extremist Groups|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=K4Khd39u0n0C&pg=PA32|publisher=[[ABDO Publishing Company]]|location=Edina, Minnesota|pages=32–|date=September 1, 2010|accessdate=21 January 2014|ISBN=978-1604538595}}</ref> The Chicago authorities became concerned about violence and passed an ordinance which required demonstrations to post large insurance bonds.<ref name="Marcovitz2010"/><ref name="Walker1994">{{cite book|first=Samuel|last=Walker|title=Hate Speech: The History of an American Controversy|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-WSsPBSK6wYC&pg=PA120|date=1994|accessdate=21 January 2014|publisher=[[University of Nebraska Press]]|location=Lincoln, Nebraska|isbn=9780803297517|pages=120–}}</ref> Collin went to the [[ACLU]] and they filed a suit.<ref name="Walker1994"/> While the case was proceeding without public notice, Collin attempted to contact other cities about holding demonstrations.<ref name="Walker1994"/> [[Skokie, Illinois]], a suburb of Chicago, responded with a notice that the group would need to post a bond, similar to the recently enacted ordinance in Chicago.<ref name="Walker1994"/> Collin's plan for his neo-Nazi group to march in uniforms through Skokie, which was heavily Jewish with numerous residents who were [[Holocaust]] survivors, generated public outrage and the media attention which Collin sought.<ref name="Kaplan2000"/><ref name="Marcovitz2010"/>

The ''[[National Socialist Party of America v. Village of Skokie]]'' case made its way to the [[Supreme Court of the United States]], which ruled on June 14, 1977 that the NSPA could march wearing uniforms with swastikas under the constitutional protections of [[freedom of speech]] and [[freedom of assembly|assembly]].<ref name="Ruling">{{cite web|url=http://caselaw.lp.findlaw.com/scripts/getcase.pl?court=US&vol=432&invol=43|title=NATIONAL SOCIALIST PARTY v. SKOKIE, 432 U.S. 43 (1977)|work=[[FindLaw]]|accessdate=21 January 2014}}</ref> Instead of marching through Skokie, Collin and a handful of NSPA members decided instead to march through Chicago, where they were outnumbered and jeered by thousands of counter-protesters.<ref name="Kaplan2000"/><ref>{{cite journal|first=Chip|last=Berlet|authorlink=Chip Berlet|editor1-first=Betty A.|editor1-last=Dobratz|editor2-first=Lisa K.|editor2-last=Walder|editor3-first=Timothy|editor3-last=Buzzell|title=Hate Groups, Racial Tension and Ethnoviolence in an Integrating Chicago Neighborhood 1976–1988|journal=Research in Political Sociology|publisher=[[Emerald Group Publishing]]|location=Bingley, West Yorkshire, England|volume=9|date=2001|pages=117–163}}</ref>

==Downfall==
Also in 1977, Koehl's NSWPP began a campaign in their paper ''White Power'' about Collin's father being Jewish,<ref name="Kaplan2000"/> including publications of what they stated were Max Simon Cohn's naturalization papers.<ref name="Kaplan2000"/> Collin and the NSPA leadership continued to deny the claim and said the images were fakes.<ref name="Kaplan2000"/>

During this time, according to [[Jeffrey Kaplan (academic)|Jeffrey Kaplan]], Covington found pictures in Frank Collin's desk that linked Collin to the sexual abuse of young boys.<ref name="Kaplan1997">{{cite book|first=Jeffrey|last=Kaplan|title=Radical Religion in America: Millenarian Movements from the Far Right to the Children of Noah|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qIilYBbxSbcC&pg=PA36|publisher=[[Syracuse University Press]]|location=Syracuse, New York|date=January 1, 2001|accessdate=January 21, 2014|isbn=9780815603962|pages=36–|quote=Covington, his rival for NSPA "power", made the fortuitous discovery (while rifling through Collin's desk) that the half-Jewish fuehrer also had a weakness for pedophilia and did not hesitate to photograph his dalliances with a number of young boys. As a result, Collin was sent to prison.}}</ref> In what Kaplan describes as a play for power in the organization, Covington and the other NSPA members turned the evidence on Collin over to the police.<ref name="Kaplan1997"/> After Collin was arrested, Covington took over leadership of the NSPA and moved the headquarters from Chicago to North Carolina.<ref name="Kaplan2000"/> A 1980 article in ''[[The New York Times]]''  reported that "Frank Collin was expelled from the American Nazi Party for illicit intercourse with minors and the use of Nazi headquarters in Chicago for purposes of sodomy with children. The report indicates that the Nazis "tipped" the police who arrested Collin.<ref>{{cite journal|first1=Irving Louis|last1=Horowitz|authorlink1=Irving Louis Horowitz|first2=Victoria Curtis|last2= Bramson|title=Skokie, the ACLU and the Endurance of Democratic Theory|journal=[[Law and Contemporary Problems]]|publisher=[[Duke University School of Law]]|location=Durham, North Carolina|date=Spring 1979|volume=43|issue=2}}</ref> Collin was convicted of [[child molestation]]<ref name="Kaplan1997"/><ref name="Bernstein2013"/> and sentenced in 1979 to seven years in prison at the [[Pontiac Correctional Center]]. He served three years.<ref name="Kaplan1997"/>

==Author==
Upon his release from prison, Collin "reinvented himself as 'Frank Joseph,' a [[New Age]] writer and [[pagan]] worshiper."<ref name="Bernstein2013">{{cite book|first=Arnie|last=Bernstein|title=Swastika Nation: Fritz Kuhn and the Rise and Fall of the German-American Bund|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jXMtAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA301|accessdate=January 21, 2014|date=2013|publisher=[[St. Martin's Press]]|location=New York City|isbn=9781250006714|pages=301}}</ref> His time in Pontiac Correctional Facility in Illinois had coincided with the period when Russell E. Burrows worked there as a prison guard.<ref>{{cite journal  | last = Wilson  | first = Joseph AP | authorlink =  | title = The Cave Who Never Was: Outsider Archaeology and Failed Collaboration in the USA  |journal = [[Public Archaeology (journal)|Public Archaeology]]  | volume = 11  | issue = 2 | pages = 75–93  | year = 2012  | url = http://www.maneyonline.com/doi/ref/10.1179/1465518712Z.0000000007 | doi = 10.1179/1465518712Z.0000000007 }}</ref> He subsequently wrote many books and articles in support of [[Burrows Cave]], an alleged cache of ancient treasure in an unrevealed location, supposedly discovered by Russell Burrows in southern Illinois."<ref name="Joseph2003">{{cite book|first=frank|last=Joseph|title=The Lost Treasure of King Juba: The Evidence of Africans in America Before Columbus |url=https://books.google.com/books/about/The_Lost_Treasure_of_King_Juba.html?id=11koDwAAQBAJ|accessdate=November 20, 2018|date=2003|publisher=[[Simon and Schuster]]|location=Rochester, VT|isbn=9781591438519|pages=224}}</ref>  In 1987 he had his first of many antiquarian books published, ''The Destruction of [[Atlantis]]: Compelling Evidence of the Sudden Fall of the Legendary Civilization''.

He wrote articles for ''[[Fate (magazine)|Fate]]'' magazine, and was the editor of ''The Ancient American'' magazine.<ref name="Press2008">{{cite book|title=American Villains, Volume 1: Joe Adonis–Jim Jones|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gu9WAAAAYAAJ|date=2008|publisher=Salem Press Inc.|location=Ipswich, Massachusetts|isbn=978-1-58765-453-4|page=125}}</ref> ''The Ancient American'' is a [[Migrationism and diffusionism|diffusionist]]-inspired magazine that focuses on what it says is evidence of ancient, [[Pre-Columbian era|pre-Columbian]] transoceanic contact between the Old World and North America. It suggests complex indigenous cultures were directly influenced by migrants from Old World Europe.<ref name="BirminghamEisenberg2000">{{cite book|first1=Robert A. |last1=Birmingham|first2=Leslie E.|last2=Eisenberg |title=Indian Mounds of Wisconsin|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wPNA_SnfrZ0C&pg=PA64|date=2000|publisher=[[University of Wisconsin Press]]|location=Madison, Wisconsin|isbn=978-0-299-16874-2|page=64}}</ref>

==Media portrayals==
*Collin has appeared as himself in several documentaries.  The video ''Chicago Nazis'' documented the Skokie march.  The [[History (U.S. TV channel)|History Channel]] special, ''Nazi America:  A Secret History'', included extensive footage of Collin. 
*He was played by [[George Dzundza]] in the 1981 [[television film]] ''[[Skokie (film)|Skokie]],'' about the planned march and court case.

