{{Infobox person |name = Henry Beeke |image = |image_size = |caption = |birth_name = |birth_date = {{Birth date|1751|1|6|df=y}} |birth_place = [[Kingsteignton]], [[Devon]], [[England]] |death_date = {{Death date and age|1837|3|9|1751|1|6|df=y}} |death_place = [[Torquay]], Devon, England |body_discovered = |death_cause = |resting_place = |residence = |nationality = British |education = |alma_mater = [[Corpus Christi, Oxford]] |occupation = Historian and theologian |home_town = |known_for = |title = [[Regius Professor of Modern History (Oxford)|Regius Professor of Modern History]] |term = 1801–1813 |predecessor = [[Thomas Nowell]] |successor = [[Edward Nares]] |spouse = |partner = |children = |parents = |relations = |signature = |website = |footnotes = }}
'''Henry Beeke''' (6 January 1751 – 9 March 1837)<ref>{{cite news |title=Death of the Dean of Bristol |newspaper=[[The Morning Post]] |date=16 March 1837 |issue=20676 }}</ref> was a historian, theologian, writer on taxation and finance, and botanist.<ref name=sheldon/>
==Career== Beeke was elected a scholar of [[Corpus Christi College, Oxford|Corpus Christi]], [[Oxford]] in May 1769. He gained a Bachelor of Arts degree in 1773, a Master of Arts degree in 1776, a Bachelor of Divinity in 1785, and a Doctorate in Divinity in 1800. In 1775 Beeke became a fellow of [[Oriel College, Oxford|Oriel College]] and was Junior Proctor of the University in 1784. Beeke was [[Regius Professor of Modern History (Oxford)|Regius Professor of Modern History]] between 1801 and 1813.<ref name=sheldon/>
Beeke was vicar of [[University Church of St Mary the Virgin|St Mary the Virgin, Oxford]] in 1782, rector of Ufton Norcot, Berkshire in 1789, Dean of Bristol in 1813, and vicar of [[Weare, Somerset|Weare]] in 1819.<ref name=sheldon/>
Beeke gained a reputation as a fiscal expert following his 1799 ''Observations on the produce of the income tax, and on its proportion to the whole income of Great Britain'', which was expanded and reprinted in 1800. Beeke's unpublished manuscripts and correspondence also show his wider interests in economics.<ref name=sheldon/>
[[Beekite]], a distinctive form of [[chalcedony]] which occurs in the preservation of fossils by [[silicification]], was named to honour Beeke.<ref name=hwb/>
Beeke was very interested in [[botany]].<ref name=druce/> He made contributions to [[Daniel Lysons (antiquarian)|Lysons']] ''[[Magna Britannia]]'' records, and corresponded with Sir [[James Edward Smith]], a fellow and first president of the [[Linnean Society of London]].<ref name=druce/> Beeke is credited as the binomial author of at least one plant species, ''Lotus pilosus'' <small>Beeke</small>, first described and published in [[Dawson Turner|Turner]] and [[Lewis Weston Dillwyn|Dillwyn]]'s Botanical Guide.<ref name=ipni/><ref name=trop/> This species was later thought to be ''Lotus uliginosus'' <small>[[Christian Schkuhr|Schkuhr]]</small>,<ref name=druce/> which is now settled as a [[Synonym (taxonomy)|synonym]] of ''[[Lotus pedunculatus]]'' <small>[[Antonio José Cavanilles|Cav.]]</small>,<ref name=tpl/> a kind of [[Lotus (genus)|trefoil]].
Beeke died at Torquay on 9 March 1837.<ref name=sheldon/>
